issue.title: [TT-6419] Querying for __typename in any graph causes a 502 error
issue.body:
This PR fixes an edge case in proxy-only mode. When you run the following query:

```graphql
query { __typename }
```

The GW panics and returns 502 for the request because the recent version of graphql-go-tools can handle this query without hitting the upstream. It maintains the type names internally. 

See https://github.com/TykTechnologies/graphql-go-tools/pull/323 for further info.

issue.title: [TT-7185]Performance Improvement
issue.body:
Change sync and publish logic to run more efficiently. 

Instead of fetching the entire list of APIs/Policies every time we create an API/Policy. We are fetching once and maintaining the diff as we create more objects. 

Instead of searching through all the existing APIs/Policies for each API/Policy we are creating/updating. The existing list of objects is parsed into maps based on the fields we are testing against (APIID, Id, Slug, and Listen Path + Domain for the APIs and MID and ID for the policies.) Those lists are updated as objects are created/updated.

This should reduce time complexity from 

N * M * M + M * P to N + M + P

where, 
N is the number of new objects (APIs or Policies)
M is the number of existing objects 
P is the payload cost for fetching the entire list of existing objects

issue.title: [TT-6419] Querying for __typename in any graph causes a 502 error
issue.body:
This PR fixes an edge case in proxy-only mode. When you run the following query:

```graphql
query { __typename }
```

The GW panics and returns 502 for the request because the recent version of graphql-go-tools can handle this query without hitting the upstream. It maintains the type names internally. 

See https://github.com/TykTechnologies/graphql-go-tools/pull/323 for further info.

issue.title: [TT-7185]Performance Improvement
issue.body:
Change sync and publish logic to run more efficiently. 

Instead of fetching the entire list of APIs/Policies every time we create an API/Policy. We are fetching once and maintaining the diff as we create more objects. 

Instead of searching through all the existing APIs/Policies for each API/Policy we are creating/updating. The existing list of objects is parsed into maps based on the fields we are testing against (APIID, Id, Slug, and Listen Path + Domain for the APIs and MID and ID for the policies.) Those lists are updated as objects are created/updated.

This should reduce time complexity from 

N * M * M + M * P to N + M + P

where, 
N is the number of new objects (APIs or Policies)
M is the number of existing objects 
P is the payload cost for fetching the entire list of existing objects

issue.title: [TT-7185]Performance Improvement
issue.body:
Change sync and publish logic to run more efficiently. 

Instead of fetching the entire list of APIs/Policies every time we create an API/Policy. We are fetching once and maintaining the diff as we create more objects. 

Instead of searching through all the existing APIs/Policies for each API/Policy we are creating/updating. The existing list of objects is parsed into maps based on the fields we are testing against (APIID, Id, Slug, and Listen Path + Domain for the APIs and MID and ID for the policies.) Those lists are updated as objects are created/updated.

This should reduce time complexity from 

N * M * M + M * P to N + M + P

where, 
N is the number of new objects (APIs or Policies)
M is the number of existing objects 
P is the payload cost for fetching the entire list of existing objects
